Title: An Act to Strengthen the Teaching of Wabanaki Studies in Maine
Official Title: An Act to Strengthen the Teaching of Wabanaki Studies in Maine
Number of Sections: 1
Source: versions - Documents and Disposition
Media Type: application/pdf
Strikethrough Detection: 4 sections found

================================================================================

Section 1:
132nd MAINE LEGISLATURE
FIRST SPECIAL SESSION-2025
Legislative Document No. 1474
H.P. 966 House of Representatives, April 3, 2025
Schools
Reference to the Committee on Education and Cultural Affairs suggested and ordered
printed.
ROBERT B. HUNT
Clerk
Presented by Representative OSHER of Orono.
Cosponsored by Senator TALBOT ROSS of Cumberland and
Representatives: BECK of South Portland, DANA of the Passamaquoddy Tribe, Speaker
FECTEAU of Biddeford, MITCHELL of Cumberland, SATO of Gorham, Senators: President
DAUGHTRY of Cumberland, HICKMAN of Kennebec, MOORE of Washington.
Printed on recycled paper
1 Be it enacted by the People of the State of Maine as follows:
2 Sec. 1. 20-A MRSA §14 is enacted to read:
3 §14. Wabanaki studies specialist
4 The Wabanaki studies specialist, referred to in this section as "the specialist," is
5 established in the department to ensure the inclusion of Wabanaki studies in the parameters
6 for essential instruction and graduation requirements as required by section 4706,
7 subsection 4.
8 1. Duties. The specialist, in consultation with the contracted Wabanaki advisors, shall:
9 A. Assist school administrative units and educators in the exploration of a wide range
10 of educational materials and resources relating to Wabanaki studies;
11 B. Identify materials and resources for implementing the instruction of Wabanaki
12 studies;
13 C. Involve organizations and individuals able and willing to assist with the
14 requirements under this subsection, including, but not limited to, museums and
15 educators; and
16 D. Make recommendations to the department regarding:
17 (1) Wabanaki studies curricula;
18 (2) Funding the instruction of Wabanaki studies in school administrative units;
19 (3) Wabanaki studies courses that count toward the requirements of teacher
20 certification; and
21 (4) Implementation of teacher education programs and summer teacher institutes.
22 2. Reporting. The specialist shall annually report to the commissioner and the Maine
23 Indian Tribal-State Commission regarding the implementation of the instruction of
24 Wabanaki studies as required by section 4706, subsection 4 and regarding:
25 A. Educational materials and resources that are appropriate to assist school
26 administrative units and educators in the State to include Wabanaki studies as required
27 by section 4706, subsection 4; and
28 B. Opportunities for professional development, training and technical assistance that
29 must be provided to assist school administrative units and educators in the State in
30 implementing Wabanaki studies as required by section 4706, subsection 4.
31 The department shall provide ongoing funding for the work of the specialist as well as
32 contracted Wabanaki advisors to advance the implementation of Wabanaki studies across
33 the State as required by section 4706, subsection 4, including funding that school
34 administrative units can apply for to fund Wabanaki studies resources.
35 Sec. 2. 20-A MRSA §4706, first ¶, as amended by PL 2021, c. 247, §1 and affected
36 by §3, is further amended to read:
37 Instruction in American history, African American studies, government, citizenship,
38 Maine studies and, the history of genocide and Wabanaki studies must be aligned with the
39 parameters for essential instruction and graduation requirements established under section
40 6209.
Page 1 - 132LR2162(01)
1 Sec. 3. 20-A MRSA §4706, sub-§2, as amended by PL 2023, c. 537, §2, is further
2 amended to read:
3 2. Maine studies. Maine history, including the Constitution of Maine, Maine
4 geography and environment and the natural, industrial and economic resources of Maine
5 and Maine's cultural and ethnic heritage, must be taught. A required component of Maine
6 studies is Wabanaki studies, and Wabanaki studies may be taught as a component of other
7 content areas, as appropriate, including but not limited to the content areas of English
8 language arts, mathematics, science and fine arts. Wabanaki studies and Maine African
9 American studies must be included in the review of content standards and performance
10 indicators of the learning results conducted in accordance with section 6209, subsection 4.
11 Wabanaki studies must address the following topics:
12 A. Wabanaki governments and political systems and their relationship with local, state,
13 national and international governments;
14 B. Wabanaki cultural systems and the experience of tribal people throughout history;
15 C. Wabanaki territories; and
16 D. Wabanaki economic systems.
17 Sec. 4. 20-A MRSA §4706, sub-§4 is enacted to read:
18 4. Wabanaki studies. Wabanaki studies must be included in the review of content
19 standards and performance indicators of the learning results conducted in accordance with
20 section 6209, subsection 4. Wabanaki studies may include social studies, English language
21 arts, mathematics, science and fine arts in accordance with this subsection. Wabanaki
22 studies must address the following topics:
23 A. Tribal governments in the State and political systems and their relationship with
24 local, state, national and international governments;
25 B. Wabanaki cultural systems and the experience of tribal people in the State
26 throughout history;
27 C. Wabanaki territories;
28 D. Wabanaki economic systems; and
29 E. Other curricula recommended by the Wabanaki studies specialist pursuant to
30 section 14.
31 The department shall, in a representative sample of schools, periodically study the
32 Wabanaki studies curricula under this subsection to assess its implementation. The
33 department shall publish its findings on the department's publicly accessible website.
34 Sec. 5. 20-A MRSA §13011, sub-§11 is enacted to read:
35 11. Wabanaki studies requirement. The state board shall adopt rules to require the
36 completion of a Wabanaki studies component in the qualifications for certifying teachers
37 in accordance with sections 13012‑A and 13013.
38 Sec. 6. 20-A MRSA c. 513 is enacted to read:
39 CHAPTER 513
Page 2 - 132LR2162(01)
1 TEACHER EDUCATION PROGRAMS IN WABANAKI STUDIES
2 §13961. Teacher education programs
3 The department shall provide funding for contracted Wabanaki advisors and educators
4 to work with the Wabanaki studies specialist pursuant to section 14 to create and implement
5 short-term courses that must be made available to all teachers throughout the State. The
6 department shall adopt rules to implement this section. Rules adopted pursuant to this
7 section are routine technical rules as defined in Title 5, chapter 375, subchapter 2-A.
8 SUMMARY
99 This bill establishes the position of Wabanaki studies specialist in the Department of
1100 Education to ensure the inclusion of Wabanaki studies in the parameters for essential
1111 instruction and graduation requirements and requires the department to provide ongoing
1122 funding for the work of the specialist as well as contracted Wabanaki advisors to advance
1133 the implementation of the instruction of Wabanaki studies across the State, including
1144 funding that school administrative units can apply for to fund Wabanaki studies resources.
1155 The bill also directs the State Board of Education to adopt rules to require the completion
1166 of a Wabanaki studies component in the qualifications for certifying teachers and requires
1177 the department to provide funding for contracted Wabanaki advisors and educators to work
1188 with the Wabanaki studies specialist to create and implement short-term courses that must
1199 be made available to all teachers throughout the State.
Page 3 - 132LR2162(01)
